Aggreko, Vallares, Vodafone, Shell: U.K., Irish Equity Preview

-- B y   J o h n   S i m p s o n
-- 
2011-06-20T06:54:50Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-06-19/allied-irish-vallares-vodafone-u-k-irish-equity-preview.html
The following is a list of companies
that may have unusual share-price changes in U.K. and Irish
markets. Stock symbols are in parentheses and prices are from
the last market close.  Futures contracts on the benchmark FTSE 100 Index slumped
0.9 percent to 5,627.5 at 7:54 a.m. in  London . The FTSE 100 on
June 17 rose 0.3 percent to 5,714.94. The FTSE All-Share Index
advanced 0.3 percent to 2,985.57 and Ireland’s ISEQ Index gained
0.8 percent to 2,886.63.  Aggreko Plc (AGK)  : The company said the rate of
underlying growth seen in the first quarter has accelerated in
the second quarter and the group forecast that it will deliver a
strong underlying performance in the first half. The shares
increased 2.4 percent to 1,911 pence.  Allied Irish Banks Plc (ALBK)  : The Dublin-based
government-controlled lender plans to sell its International
Financial Services business, which offers aircraft leasing and
other services, the Sunday Times reported, without saying where
it got the information. The shares jumped 5.3 percent to 15.8
euro cents.  Lloyds Banking Group Plc (LLOY)  : Chief Executive Officer
Antonio Horta-Osorio plans to prioritize the bank’s Halifax unit
after a review of its strategy, the Sunday Telegraph reported,
without saying where it got the information. The shares added
0.7 percent to 48.4 pence.  Rolls-Royce Holdings Plc (RR/ LN): The world’s second-
largest maker of  jet engines  signed an agreement to be the
exclusive engine provider for an enhanced version of the Airbus
SAS A350-1000 aircraft. The shares increased 0.2 percent to
598.5 pence.  Royal Dutch Shell Plc (RDSA)  :  Europe ’s largest oil
company and its partner Mitsubishi Corp. are preparing to begin
a delayed $12.5 billion natural-gas project in  Iraq , Hans
Nijkamp, vice president and country chairman was cited as saying
on the website of Energy Exchange, citing an interview. The
shares advanced 0.8 percent to 2,122.5 pence.  Southern Cross Healthcare Plc (SCHE LN): The financially
troubled U.K. care-home provider is in talks with lenders to
extend debt covenant waivers on its loans to the end of October
from the end of June, the Sunday Telegraph reported, without
saying where it got the information. The shares slumped 5.2
percent to 8 pence.  Vodafone Group Plc (VOD)  : The mobile-phone company said
it is starting a 4 billion pound ($6.5 billion) share buyback
program “to return a significant part of the proceeds of such
disposal to shareholders.” The stock fell 0.2 percent to 159.7
pence.  To contact the reporter on this story:
